tens of thousands of years, new social roles-notably spouse, father, in-laws, and grandparents-have co-evolved with new technologies and symbolic meanings to produce the human species, in the absence of significant biological evolution. We are biocultural creatures, Marks argues, fully comprehensible by recourse to neither our real ape ancestry nor our imaginary cultureless biology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aHuman evolution. 0aSocial evolution. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Physical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311062111208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016z978311065748740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520961197423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520961197.jpg  a978-3-11-062111-2  UC Press eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-065748-7  UCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles